ographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gai","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 蓋, meaning ‘lid’ or ‘build’ in Chinese: (i) from the placename Gai (蓋), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Warring States period (475–221  BC ). (ii) adopted as the surname by the Ge Lou (蓋樓) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Italian (Piedmont): from French surname Gai, Gay literally ‘cheerful’; in some cases it is possible a nickname from dialect word <i>gai</i> ‘jay’.","Italian (Tuscany): patronymic or plural form of <i>Gaio</i>,   Gaia  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Ritsuko, Takashi, Akiko, Chitose, Hidetaka, Hisashi, Kaoru, Kumiko, Mamoru, Masakazu, Masaru, Masayuki.","Japanese: original meaning could be 貝 ‘shell’, but the name is written phonetically with two characters 甲斐 ‘tortoise shell’ and ‘beauty’. Though the surname is found mostly in the island of Kyūshū, some families could have connections with the ancient province of Kai (now Yamanashi prefecture) in the mountains of central Honshū, whose name is written with the two characters above.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 蓋, see   Gai   1."]},{"name":"Gaia","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Camillo, Angelo, Sylvio.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Gaia</i>, feminine form of <i>Gaio</i> (from Latin <i>Caius</i>, <i>Gaius</i>).","Portuguese: habitational name from Gaia in northern Portugal."]},{"name":"Cai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Li, Hong, Xin, Yang, Feng, Jian, Liming, Ming, Rong, Yi, Hui.  Vietnamese Quan, Anh, Chau, Dinh, Huong Thi, Huyen, Khiem, Loan Kim, Long, Nga, Nhi, Oanh.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 蔡, originally referring to ‘the tortoise used in ancient rituals of divination’ in Chinese: from the placename Cai (蔡), a fief (originally located in Shangcai in Henan province) which was granted to Du, also known as Cai Shu (蔡叔), son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (1152–1056  BC ). Later Cai Shu plotted rebellions and was eventually sent into exile. But his son, Hu, also known as Cai Zhong (蔡仲), was a revered man and was granted the fief of Cai (蔡), which later became a state during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu in 447  BC , the name of the state was adopted as a surname.","Catalan (Girona and Alicante; <b>Caí</b>): possibly from the Biblical personal name <i>Caín</i> ‘Cain’."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Philip de Gai Lord of Wooton Basset was born in 1122, in England as the son of Stephen de Gai. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Cecily Berkeley. He died in 1177, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1122–1177":"1122–1177","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1159–1229":"1159–1229","1170–1243":"1170–1243","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1190":"1190","1159":"1159","1135":"1135","1122":"1122","1177":"1177","1100":"1100","1243":"1243","12 April 1170":"12. aprill 1170","1170":"1170","1229":"1229","Stroud, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Stroud, Gloucester